Besides land, the Swedish-speaking areas are concentrated on the West Coast in Ostrobothnia , the South Coast regions of Uusimaa and Eastern Uusimaa , and the region of Finland Proper .

Under the present regulations, valid until 2012, of 416 Finnish municipalities, 19 are Swedish-speaking (including 16 in land). 43 municipalities are bilingual; of these, 22 have a Swedish-speaking majority and 21 a Finnish-speaking one. The remaining 354 municipalities are monolingually Finnish-speaking.
The language law does not apply in land ( Ahvenanmaa in Finnish), an autonomous province that is monolingually Swedish.
[ edit ] References

Lohja is the only municipality to make use of this special provision. The 3,000-speaker rule was introduced as the proportion of Swedish residents of Turku (approximately 9,000 people) was less than 6%. Additionally, the 3,000-speaker rule applies in Vantaa (which has around 6,000 Swedish-speaking residents); other municipalities are bilingual by virtue of the percentage rule.

Both languages are official . At the local level, a municipality can officially use Finnish, Swedish or be bilingual. The Finnish language law provides for bilingualism if both languages represent at least 8% of the population, or at least 3,000 speakers. A previously bilingual municipality retains its status until the proportion falls below 6%, but a municipality can choose to retain bilingualism even if the percentage drops below 6.
In Finland 91.5% of the population speak Finnish, and 5.5% Swedish (as of December 31, 2006).
General
This list includes all Finnish cities and municipalities in which Swedish has official status at the local level .
More than 17,000 Swedish Finns live in officially monolingual Finnish municipalities, and are thus not represented on the map.
